Kubernetes NetworkPolicy - Ingress & Egress?

What is NetworkPolicy?

NetworkPolicy is a Kubernetes resource that controls traffic to and from your pods. Think of it like a firewall rule for your pods — you decide who can talk to whom inside the cluster.

By default, all pods can communicate with each other freely. Once you apply a NetworkPolicy, only the traffic you explicitly allow will work.

Ingress (Incoming Traffic)

Ingress controls who can send traffic TO your pod.

The question it answers: "Who is allowed to talk to me?"


Egress (Outgoing Traffic)

Egress controls where your pod is allowed to send traffic.

The question it answers: "Who am I allowed to talk to?"

Both Ingress and Egress Together:

apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: backend-full-policy
spec:
  podSelector:
    matchLabels:
      app: backend
  policyTypes:
  - Ingress
  - Egress

  ingress:
  - from:
    - podSelector:
        matchLabels:
          app: frontend
    ports:
    - port: 8080

  egress:
  - to:
    - podSelector:
        matchLabels:
          app: database
    ports:
    - port: 5432


Other Useful Selectors
namespaceSelector — allow traffic from a specific namespace:

ingress:
- from:
  - namespaceSelector:
      matchLabels:
        name: production   # only pods from production namespace


ipBlock — allow traffic from a specific IP range:

egress:
- to:
  - ipBlock:
      cidr: 10.0.0.0/24   # allow this IP range
      except:
      - 10.0.0.5/32        # but block this specific IP


Key Differences at a Glance

                Ingress                      Egress
--------------------------------------------------------------
Direction       Incoming traffic             Outgoing traffic
Question        Who can talk to me?          Who can I talk to?
Keyword         from                         to
Use case        Protect your pod from        Prevent your pod from calling
                unwanted access              unauthorized services
